\begin_layout Abstract
Meta-analysis, the statistical analysis of results from separate studies,
 is a fundamental building block of science.
 But the assumptions of classical meta-analysis models are not satisfied
 whenever publication bias is present, which causes inconsistent parameter
 estimates.
 Hedges' selection function model takes publication bias into account, but
 estimating and infering with this model is hard and sometimes yields unbelievab
le results.
 Using a generalized Gleser–Hwang theorem, we show there is no confidence
 set of guaranteed finite diameter for the parameters of Hedges' selection
 model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A meta-analysis is a statistical analysis that quantiatively combines results
 from separate scientific studies.
 When the studies measure the same phenomenon, pooling of information allows
 us to predict the common effect size with larger precision than we could
 have done with one study alone.
 Meta-analyses are ubiquitous in the empirical sciences and forms a key
 component of most systematic reviews such as Cochrane's reviews 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Higgins2019-vv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most meta-analytic techniques assume honest and unbiased reporting of results.
 But there is ample evidence that the scientific literature is not unbiased,
 as studies with
\emph on
 
\emph default
significant 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-values tend to be published with a greater probability than other studies
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Easterbrook1991-ph"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, a phenomenon called publication bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sterling1959publication"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 When publication bias is present, there is no reason to trust the results
 of meta-analytic methods that do not account for it, as the parameter estimates
 will be incosistent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Carter2019-rw"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hedges' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "hedges1992modeling"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 publication bias model takes publication explicitly into account using
 a selection model, and is arguably the most appropriate model for publication
 bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "moss2019modelling,Carter2019-rw"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Despite there being an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{R}$
\end_inset

 package for maximum likelihood estimation of this model, called 
\begin_inset Formula $\texttt{weightr}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Coburn2019-ec"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, it has not yet taken off.
 Its maximum likelihood estimation methods are numerically unstable and
 its estimates can be off even when they converge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Coburn2019-ec,Stanley2005-ng"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The estimate of the mean effect size may be negative and of unrealistically
 large magnitude, and the estimated heterogeneity parameter might be improbably
 large.
 It turns out there are ridges in the likelihood function that can be linked
 to this behavior 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McShane2016-rb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but it has not been stated in clear terms exactly what the problem is.
 The purpose of this note is to show there is no confidence set for the
 mean effect size that has finite diameter with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 In the terminology of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "berger1999integrated"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Hedges' publication bias model belongs to the 
\emph on
Gleser–Hwang
\emph default
 class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hedges' publication bias model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most popular and well-known meta-analysis method is the random effects
 model with normal likelihoods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hedges1998fixed"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Written in hierarchical notation, it equals
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\theta_{i} & \sim & N(\theta_{0},\tau),\nonumber \\
x_{i}\mid\theta_{i},\sigma & \sim & N(\theta_{i},\sigma_{i}).\label{eq:conditional random effects density}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the standard deviation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th study.
 Following the convention in meta-analysis, we assume all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

s to be known.
 The mean parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the population effect size, 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\theta_{0},\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the effect size distribution, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the heterogeneity parameter.
 The purpose of the effect size distribution is to model the fact that most
 effect size estimates plugged into a meta-analysis do not appear to measure
 the same phenomenon.
 By integrating out 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

, we find the density of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x_{i};\theta_{0},\tau,\sigma_{i})=\phi\left(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sqrt{\tau^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2}}\right),\label{eq:random effects meta-analysis model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the density of a normal random variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will assume that the random effects meta-analysis model is true in the
 absence of publication bias.
 The mechanisms that cause publication bias modify the density in a suitable
 way.
 First we consider the case when only significant studies at some specified
 level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are published.
 Assuming one-sided tests, the 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-values are 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}=\Phi(-x_{i}/\sigma_{i})$
\end_inset

, or normal one-sided 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-values.
 We will only deal with with one-sided 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-values in this paper, as there is usually, but not always, just one direction
 that is interesting.
 A one-sided 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-value can also be used if the researchers reported a two-sided value, since
 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.05$
\end_inset

 for a two-sided hypothesis corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.025$
\end_inset

 for a one-sided hypothesis, et cetera.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}=\Phi^{-1}(1-\alpha)$
\end_inset

, the cut-off for significance at level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
basic publication bias model
\emph default
 has density
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sigma_{i})=\Phi\left(\frac{\theta_{0}-c_{\alpha}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}}\right)^{-1}\phi\left(x;\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}\right)1[x_{i}/\sigma_{i}>c_{\alpha}],\label{eq:selection for significance model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is a truncated normal.
 This model for publication bias was introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hedges1984estimation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in the context of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic publication bias model is unrealistic.
 It requires that no non-significant studies are published.
 But even in the fields most severely affected by publication bias, such
 as psychology, a non-negligble number of non-significant studies are published
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Motyl2017-dx"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the basic publication bias model does not allow for different
 cut-offs for significance.
 For instance, it is likely that some editors will accept studies reaching
 a significance at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.025$
\end_inset

, corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}/\sigma_{i}>1.96$
\end_inset

 but not at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

, corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}/\sigma_{i}>1.64$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These problems can be rectified by adopting the selection model for publication
 bias of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "iyengar1988selection"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which models the following scenario.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Publication bias scenario.

\series default
 Alice the editor receives a study with the 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-value 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 Her publication decision is a random function of this 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-value.
 That is, she will publish the study with some probability 
\begin_inset Formula $w(u)$
\end_inset

 and reject it with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-w(u)$
\end_inset

.
 Every study you will ever read in Alice's journal has survived this selection
 mechanism, the rest are lost forever.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w(u_{i})$
\end_inset

 be a function of the 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-value 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}=1-\Phi(-x_{i}/\sigma_{i})$
\end_inset

 taking values in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $w(u_{i})$
\end_inset

 is a probability for every 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

, and the selection model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}\right)\propto\phi\left(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}\right)w(u)\label{eq:iyengar-greenhouse model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

models the publication bias scenario exactly.
 This model can be viewed as a rejection sampling procedure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "flury1990acceptance,von1951various"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 serves as proposal distribution for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hedges1992modeling"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 studies the selection model when 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is a step function.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be a vector with elements 
\begin_inset Formula $0=\alpha_{0}<\alpha_{1}<\ldots<\alpha_{K}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-ary non-negative, non-increasing vector satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Define the step function 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 based on 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w(u;\rho,\alpha)=\sum_{k=1}^{K}\rho_{k}1_{(\alpha_{k-1},\alpha_{k}]}(u).\label{eq:step function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We will call the selection model with a step function 
\emph on
Hedges' publication bias model.
 
\emph default
Its density is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}\right)\propto\sum_{k=1}^{K}\rho_{k}\phi\left(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}\right)1_{(\alpha_{k-1},\alpha_{k}]}(u_{i}).\label{eq:hedges model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The interpretation of Hedges' publication bias model is simple.
 When the editor receives a study with 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-value 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, she finds the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in(\alpha_{j-1},\alpha_{j}]$
\end_inset

 and accepts with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=1$
\end_inset

, she always accepts when 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in[0,\alpha_{1}]$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is non-increasing since a publication decision based solely on 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-values should always act favorably towards higher 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-values.
 The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta_{0},\tau,\rho)$
\end_inset

 of the model are identified when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is fixed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "moss2019modelling"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hedges' publication bias models allows both for non-significant studies
 to be published and allows the editor to act differently towards 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.025$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.05$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, the model can approximate any selection function 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 by increasing the number of steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is non-increasing allows us to write Hedges' model as a mixture model on
 the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}\right)=\sum_{k=1}^{K}\pi^{k}f^{k}\left(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}\right).\label{eq:mixture model formulation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{K}$
\end_inset

 is a normal density, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{k},k<K$
\end_inset

 are normal densities truncated to 
\begin_inset Formula $[\Phi^{-1}(1-\alpha_{j-1}),\Phi^{-1}(1-\alpha))$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{k}$
\end_inset

 are mixture probabilities, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{k}>0$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{K}\pi^{k}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The mixture probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{k}$
\end_inset

 are functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta_{0},\tau,\sigma_{i},\rho)$
\end_inset

, see the appendix (p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "eq:pi_i formula"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) for their formula.
 This representation will come in handy later on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hedges' publication bias model models 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-value based publication bias directly, there is no approximation involved.
 If you believe in the random effects meta-analysis model and the 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-value based publication bias scenario, Hedges' publication bias model is
 simply the correct model.
 Most statistical methods correcting for publication bias in the literature
 either do not make use of an explicit statistical model or do not estimate
 the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, the funnel funnel plot of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Egger1997-rd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a graphical method, while the trim-and-fill method of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Duval2000-ct"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a non-parametric method based on making the funnel plot symmetric.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Stanley2005-ng,stanley2014meta"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discuss misspecified regression-based estimators of the corrected effect
 size 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 based on the fixed effect Hedges' publication bias model.
 The estimating 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-curve method of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Simonsohn2014-cn"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-uniform of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Van_Aert2016-cu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 are two methods for dealing with publication bias hailing from psychology.
 Both are based on a variant of the basic publication bias model, but with
 fixed instead of random effects, and both employ somewhat unusual estimation
 methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McShane2016-rb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since there is ample evidence of heterogeneity in meta-analysis, restricting
 oneself to the fixed effects meta-analysis is a mistake.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hedges' model has some downsides.
 It models only bias due to selection of 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-values, not every source of bias, such as language bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Egger1998-kj"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Second, it may not be best model for 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-hacking 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "simmons2011false"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moss2019modelling"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 propose a model that may be more successful at correcting for 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-hacking.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Estimation of Hedges' model is difficult.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Section 6.3"
key "Stanley2005-ng"
literal "false"

\end_inset

