\begin_layout Standard
Well-behaved confidence sets for Hedges publication bias model do not exist,
 but well-behaved credibility sets do.
 Bayesian estimation of Hedges model can be made routine, as it is easy
 to find uncontroverisal priors for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 In practical meta-analyses we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 cannot be large, ad is likely to be close to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, since since many effects can be understood as the aggregation
 of many small effects, the central limit theorem justifies using a normal
 prior.
 As we want to remove prior mass from negative 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

s of large magnitude, 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,1)$
\end_inset

 is a decent standard prior.
 Similarily, a half-normal is a reasonable prior for the heterogeneity parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moss2019modelling"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 employed these priors on several examples.
 
\end_layout

